<canvas id="qr-canvas" width="300" height="300"></canvas>
<p>
  <button id="save-qr-image-btn" hidden>Save QR Code</button>
  <img id="saved-qr-image" src="" hidden />
</p>
<script>
  // Add your JavaScript code here
</script>
```

3. Implement the JavaScript code to access the user's camera and start the stream:

```javascript
const video = document.getElementById('qr-video');
const canvas = document.getElementById('qr-canvas');
const saveBtn = document.getElementById('save-qr-image-btn');
const savedImg = document.getElementById('saved-qr-image');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia({ video: { facingMode: 'environment' } })
  .then(stream => {
    video.srcObject = stream;
    video.setAttribute('playsinline', true);
    video.play();
    scanQRCode();
  })
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

4. Add the `scanQRCode()` function that will constantly take snapshots from the video stream, try to detect QR codes, and draw the frame in the canvas:

```javascript
function scanQRCode() {
  requestAnimationFrame(scanQRCode);
  ctx.drawImage(video, 0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

  const imageData = ctx.getImageData(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
  const decodedQRCode = jsQR(imageData.data, imageData.width, imageData.height);
  if (decodedQRCode) {
    console.log("QR Code Detected:", decodedQRCode.data);
    saveBtn.hidden = false;
  }
}
```

5. Implement the save functionality using the `html2canvas` library:

```javascript
saveBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
  html2canvas(canvas).then(canvas => {
    const imageURL = canvas.toDataURL('image/png');
    savedImg.src = imageURL;
    savedImg.hidden = false;
  });
});
```

That's it! You now have a simple web application that detects and saves QR codes from a live camera stream using JavaScript. Please note that this application should be served over HTTPS, as most browsers restrict camera access on insecure connections.

Yes, you can use React in a Chrome extension's content script. A content script is a JavaScript file that runs in the context of web pages, allowing you to interact with DOM of web pages. You can use React in a content script just like you do in a regular web page.

Here's how you can go about it:

1. **Create a React component**: You can create a simple React component on its own file, say, `myComponent.js`. It doesn't have to be complex. It can be just a simple setup with JSX and a render method.

2. **Import your React component**: In your content script, you can straight up import your component. It's just a JavaScript file so it works the same way.

3. **Initialize your React component**: Create a reference to the DOM node where you want to render your component. Then call ReactDOM.render() to render your component to that section of the DOM.

Here's a simplified example:

```javascript
// contentScript.js

// Load the React component
import myComponent from './myComponent';

// Choose a specific element to append the React component
const selectedElement = document.getElementById('my-element');

// Render the React component to the chosen DOM node
ReactDOM.render(<myComponent />, selectedElement);
```

```javascript
// myComponent.js

import React from 'react';

const myComponent = (props) => (
  <div>
    <h1>Hello, {props.name}</h1>
  </div>
);

export default myComponent;
```

In this example, the `contentScript.js` is your content script, which imports and renders the `myComponent.js` React component.

Remember to include your components' files in the `content_scripts` section of your `manifest.json` file:

```json
{
  "name": "My Extension",
  "version": "1.0",
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": [
        "<all_urls>"
      ],
      "js": ["contentScript.js"],
      "run_at": "document_end",
      "all_frames": true
    }
  ],
  "background": {
    "scripts": ["backgroundScript.js"]
  }
}
```

In this manifest, the `contentScripts` section specifies that `contentScript.js` (which includes `myComponent.js`) should run on any website.

Please note that although this will work, it's worth noting that Chrome extension content scripts have some limitations due to the content script's isolated environment and the restrictions of running inside the web page's context. Always ensure your extension's functionality works within these limitations.

