public class Controller : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float moveSpeed = 10.0f;
    private Rigidbody rb;

    void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
    }

    void FixedUpdate()
    {
        float moveHorizontal = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal");
        float moveVertical = Input.GetAxis("Vertical");

        Vector3 movement = new Vector3(moveHorizontal, 0, moveVertical);

        rb.AddForce(movement * moveSpeed);
    }
}
```
In the `Start()` function, the script gets a reference to the Rigidbody component attached to the object you want to control. This is so that it can apply forces to the object.

In `FixedUpdate()`, the script gets the horizontal and vertical input using `Input.GetAxis()`. These methods return a float value that represents the horizontal or vertical input from the analog stick of the controller. The two values are then combined into a single `Vector3` to make the movement more intuitive.

Finally, the `Rigidbody.AddForce()` method is used to apply forces to the object. The force is calculated as the direction taken from the input vectors plus the moveSpeed multiplied by a direction. You can adjust the moveSpeed variable to change the sensitivity or speed of the movement.

You'll also need to assign this script to a GameObject in your Unity scene, and assign a Rigidbody component to that same object.

